1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Today is Wednesday, July 13, 2011. My name is Joe Manier of the Southern Laurel History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

3
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:32,000
I'm in Washington, D.C. in the Jefferson Building of the Library of Congress, which is the Art of For John Bishop.

4
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:45,000
And we are here to complete an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

5
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:54,000
And we're especially pleased and honored today to have with us both Mr. Simeon Booker on the right on the screen and Mr. Moses Newson.

6
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:04,000
And I'm here to gentlemen with long histories of engagement with the Civil Rights era and beyond and before as journalists.

7
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:10,000
So Mr. Newson, Mr. Booker, thank you very much for troubling to make the trip here today and sit down. Thank you.

8
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Good to be here.

9
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:22,000
I thought I might start Mr. Booker with just having you tell us a little bit about your entry into your professional journalistic work when you joined in 1942.

10
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:29,000
You joined the Afro-American as a reporter at $18 a week.

11
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Well, I'm just trying to think back that floor.

12
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:58,000
I was quite close to the Afro because the publisher called Murphy and my uncle, Jason Waring, Jr., the principal of Downing Town Industrial School in Pennsylvania, reclasses me to all of it.

13
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:10,000
And so I always had a yearning for journalism and for the cause of call, Murphy.

14
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:18,000
And I yearned to go to Harvard because of their joint studies there.

15
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Indeed you'd go to, you would go in the early 50s to Harvard as an event, though.

16
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:39,000
I did eventually but I started off working as a reporter on the, uh, uh, uh, uh, uh, uh, uh, uh, calling post.

17
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Well, the call post, but I went from the Afro to the call post.

18
00:02:45,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Then I applied for a Harvard Neeman and one of Neeman, one of the medical post, when I finished, I then lived in Maya wanted not to go back to call post, but to go to Washington, which I thought would be an event.

19
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:22,000
But when I talked to the publisher, he said that, uh, come, I'll give you a job and figure this occurred.

20
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:29,000
I worked in the government as a clerk for a few months till opening came.

21
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:41,000
But then when the opening came, I found that being at the post, I was way so far down the ladder that all my bad ground experience at Harvard was of no use.

22
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:45,000
I was a Cuban, like a Cuban poet.

23
00:03:45,000 --> 00:04:02,000
But then I decided to leave and go with Johnny Johnson, who was opening up a small pocket magazine called Jet, and I went to Chicago.

24
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:17,000
And after a few years, I started to open a Washington bureau, and he named me and started finding the candidate, so I chose myself and came to Washington.

25
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,000
I think that was an excellent hire.

26
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:29,000
Let me pick that story back up in just a minute, but I want to turn to Mr. Newsson and ask a little bit about your entry into your professional journalistic work.

27
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:35,000
I know that as a young man, you entered the US Navy and went on from there.

28
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:44,000
Yes, and after I came out of the Navy, I stuck around a while and did some work with my father.

29
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:57,000
And I had always been interested in a lot of the newspapers that we got from different places, Pittsburgh, Korea, Chicago, defender, and some of those.

30
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:03,000
They were telling quite a different story from what we got in the State paper.

31
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:11,000
At that time, Dynett Flore, most everybody was taking a time union out of Jacksonville.

32
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:32,000
And I saw a lot of things, a lot of stories that interest me, and being someone who was sort of interested in helping people, and maybe trying to help change the situation we were living on the right time, I chose that as a good feel to go into.

33
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:45,000
And I started out at Storke College in West Virginia for a while, and then went to the School of Journalism at Lincoln University in Missouri.

34
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:50,000
And graduated there in the summer of 1952.

35
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:56,000
And my first job was with the twice-day defender in Memphis.

36
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:00,000
That was one of the defendants' same papers.

37
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:09,000
And spent five years there doing some of everything, covered anything and everything that came along.

38
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:12,000
Sure.

39
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:26,000
These were years, obviously, when the pace and emphasis of racial change was accelerating, but also meeting lots of early and very unfathomable pediments.

40
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:35,000
And I want to just ask a little bit about some of the early and substantial stories that you began to cover.

41
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Mr. Newsson, I think when you were in Memphis with the defender, you did work in both 55 in Clinton, excuse me, in Hoxie, Arkansas, and then in 56 in Clinton, Tennessee.

42
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:00,000
And I wonder if you can recall some of the details of those very early efforts at school this year.

43
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:12,000
Yeah, those were very interesting entries and entries into the coverage of school desegregation.

44
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:26,000
At that time, we had heard a lot of things about how difficult it would be and places where there were lots and numbers of black citizens were supposed to be some of the toughest areas.

45
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:33,000
And places where there were small numbers of black were supposed to be pretty easy situations.

46
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:36,000
Try not not to be that way.

47
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:53,000
In Hoxie, actually, a media people were invited to come into the classrooms, ride the buses with the kids, come in, talk to some of the teachers in the classrooms, and that sort of thing.

48
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:02,000
It was pretty unusual and effective as it didn't happen anywhere else that I went.

49
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:06,000
It went along pretty smoothly there for a while.

50
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:11,000
And as you know, there had people who went around trying to stir up problems.

51
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:16,000
People started to age a cutter and John Kasper.

52
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:28,000
They got in there after the schools they got started and fired up a lot of people along with KKK and some of the others.

53
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:34,000
And eventually, they had a lot of problems there.

54
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:37,000
John was sort of a different story.

55
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:43,000
At the time, there were about 5,000, maybe 4,000 people in the city.

56
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:47,000
Only about 200 of them were black.

57
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:49,000
And sort of a strange situation.

58
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:51,000
That's a hilly country.

59
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:55,000
Most of the black people there lived up on what they called Foley Hill.

60
00:08:55,000 --> 00:09:03,000
You went up one way and you drove around the area and you came back down the same way.

61
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:07,000
They didn't have a high school there for blacks at all.

62
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:13,000
So the blacks had to go to different counties to go to high school.

63
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:21,000
And these kids who were going to integrate the school, they had to walk down this hill every morning.

64
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:29,000
People line up on both sides and yell stuff and throw stuff and that sort of thing.

65
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Back in those days, there was no public accommodation situation.

66
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:41,000
You had to find some place to stay when you had covered these stories.

67
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:49,000
My situation in this case is that I was standing over in Knoxville, which is about 18 miles away.

68
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:55,000
Every evening after things took place, I'd head back out to Knoxville.

69
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:07,000
That's when the people would come down from the hills and they'd be shooting up guns and they'd be shooting off our crackers and trying to intimidate people.

70
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:08,000
That sort of thing.

71
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:15,000
There were a lot of trouble inside the school, but eventually it worked out and then it got bad.

72
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:19,000
There was a minister just to let you know how bad there was.

73
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:26,000
There was a white minister who walked down the hill one day with these kids and he lost his job.

74
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:29,000
He got chased out of town.

75
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:37,000
Eventually the governor had to call out the National Guard there to bring peace in that situation.

76
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:38,000
Yeah.

77
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:45,000
Mr. Booker, I want to ask about...

78
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:49,000
You were in Chicago in 55 and not yet moved to DC, I think.

79
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:50,000
Is that right?

80
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:51,000
That's right.

81
00:10:51,000 --> 00:11:02,000
When you first made your trip down, I think your first trip to Mississippi as I have read was to go down and to cover the work of two gentlemen, Gus Lee and Mr. George Lee,

82
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Pastor Lee, who were doing voter registration work in Humphrey's County, Mrs. Lee.

83
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:15,000
When I went down, Emmett Till was some Chicago, many Till.

84
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:28,000
When he was killed, I decided to never make a terrific story for Jit.

85
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:34,000
I was told the photographer and the self decide we would go down.

86
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:37,000
To check out, I never didn't.

87
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:46,000
I was born in Baltimore, grew up in Young Sound of High, and never covered ourselves at all.

88
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:52,000
So going into Mississippi was completely new to me.

89
00:11:52,000 --> 00:12:08,000
We went down to check on his death, how the two men had gone in and killed him because he whistled it.

90
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:16,000
I don't know if it was one of the wives, and we went down for that.

91
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:24,000
The silo kit was different from what I expected.

92
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:37,000
You also, I think, had developed a very close journalistic connection to Mrs. Till, maybe Till Brown.

93
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:50,000
When I was with her, we went, remember being with her, when we stayed up all night,

94
00:12:50,000 --> 00:13:05,000
and when we were in the body, we came in from Mississippi, and when it did come, she demanded that the body be open.

95
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:11,000
So the world could see what they did to my boy.

96
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:28,000
When they opened the clasket in the funeral, I remember a piece of his skull fell off, and my photographer went over and picked it up and put it back on before he shot a picture.

97
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:36,000
It was a very crucial scene, but she was a tough lady.

98
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:46,000
Let me ask you many questions about coming up that theme, but I wanted to ask about your photographer, David Jackson.

99
00:13:46,000 --> 00:14:02,000
He was very good, a very fun photographer, and he could handle all of the murder cases that came up.

100
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:12,000
And those days the cameras were big. They went a little way to put in your pocket.

101
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:19,000
So there was a very dangerous thing to be a photographer, and to work in the silo.

102
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:28,000
And he was a pretty brave fellow. He just dared to do anything.

103
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:42,000
He was thinking about the till case and about school desegregation. I'm interested in hearing from both of you thoughts about how the black press was evolving in the mid-50s.

104
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:51,000
54, it's been a very tough year without recession and a lot of retrenchment in circulation figures for a lot of black newspapers.

105
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:57,000
And then these stories pay the press forward in certain new ways. I'm interested in your thoughts about that.

106
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:04,000
The jet circle just took off when they ran the picture. They had the reprint.

107
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:14,000
First time they ever reprinted jet magazines, and there were a lot of interest in that case.

108
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:28,000
The whole entire black community was becoming aware of the need to do something about it.

109
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:40,000
Yeah, I think starting with the school ruling in 1954, South was always a pretty tough place.

110
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:49,000
And places like Mississippi were just backwards, raceless baking.

111
00:15:49,000 --> 00:16:10,000
And we got this real hateful climate where people in the Congress and other leaders were speaking forcefully about the fact that they were not going to integrate schools.

112
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:28,000
And we were having a lot of problems. You mentioned George Lee, one of the guys who was killed just for trying to get black folks to register the vote.

113
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:40,000
He was actually one of two people who killed in 1954, just before, in 1955, just before Emmett Till was killed.

114
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:52,000
And the thing about these murders is that nobody was being convicted. And neither of those two cases, nobody was convicted.

115
00:16:52,000 --> 00:17:12,000
I went down for the funeral of George Lee. And strangely enough, a lot of people went down because that was one of the first times that Roy Wilkins had taken over as head of the NAACP's operation body.

116
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:22,000
And people wanted to see how tough he was going to be, how strong he was going to be down in Mississippi.

117
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:32,000
But I think Mississippi had a reputation for being one of the worst places.

118
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:43,000
And you're asking about the media, the two papers in Mississippi and Jackson, Mississippi.

119
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:53,000
To my mind were some of the worst. There were a lot of bad ones as far as coverage of civil rights was concerned.

120
00:17:53,000 --> 00:18:12,000
But they were two of the worst. The entire climate, not just the people being killed during the slightest type of things, the case with Emmett Till.

121
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:23,000
He's supposed to have whistled at some woman, Bryant, who ran a store with her husband Roy.

122
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:34,000
It happened that they were out of town. The husband was out of town. And he's had brother, mylam, ZW Mylam, were out of town.

123
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:41,000
They hadn't heard about that thing until one of Till's young friends mentioned it.

124
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:52,000
So as soon as we heard about him being missing, that he had possibly whistled at a white woman, I went down and shot some pictures around.

125
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:58,000
His little whistled stop place, four or five stores, and pretty much nothing else.

126
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:04,000
I interviewed grandfather at a cotton field where he was doing some work there.

127
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:10,000
He really wanted to stay down. He said that was going to be one of his most profitable years.

128
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:22,000
He was a chef woman with this German guy. But his wife left immediately. I hated back to Chicago.

129
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:36,000
It didn't take long in those days to get a trial on the way. We just finished something that went on for three years.

130
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:48,000
I think they killed him around August 28th or something like that. And we were down there for the trial on September 19th.

131
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:53,000
So that was very short period.

132
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:03,000
To me, I guess I was about 28 at the time. It was a pretty tough situation down there.

133
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:07,000
Some of the guys were more veteran, so I had a little different.

134
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:14,000
But it was a pretty tense situation for me. I had gone down early and interviewed this year.

135
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:19,000
George Smith, who's actually made the arrest.

136
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:24,000
When we got over, he was someone you could talk to, you could interview.

137
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:30,000
When we got over, whether the trial was being held, or when Tallah had a county, a different story.

138
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:36,000
We ran it to Sheriff's Trader. He hadn't done much of a job.

139
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:42,000
I was trying to get witnesses to do something in the case.

140
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:55,000
I guess I was selected one day to go out and try to with some NAAC people to see if we could round up some witnesses who would be there.

141
00:20:55,000 --> 00:21:03,000
I actually sure was going to testify and did testify on behalf of the guys who had done the murder.

142
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:11,000
We changed clothes and went out wearing something, something like plantation workers would use to be wearing.

143
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:18,000
We did round up a couple of people who did testify on the case.

144
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:28,000
I think it was important. The NAACP was pretty much the hell end of the case.

145
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:46,000
There were three people who went along the wall in NAACP. Our driver was Megga Evers, who drove us to all those bank-bite plantations and plantings where we were trying to find witnesses back there.

146
00:21:46,000 --> 00:22:03,000
I was quite interested. Later, I think that night, some of the other press guys, Black and White, went out with police officers and they made arrangements to have a couple of people testify on the trial.

147
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:08,000
Let's pause here.

148
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:19,000
We're back after a short break. Mr. Newsom, you were talking about some of the strategies and approaches you used in and around money,

149
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:28,000
especially during the trial. For example, changing clothes and going out to search for witnesses in that very unusual and exceptional situation.

150
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:46,000
I'd be interested in having both of you talk a little bit about generally how your ideas and strategies for going into communities in very tense situations as Black reporters and doing work in very tense and potentially dangerous situations.

151
00:22:46,000 --> 00:23:05,000
We just started a string of systems and that was in all the rural areas and so we had people who would submit articles or ideas every week and we would pay for the best one.

152
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:23,000
These people now only became informers for the article, but they also became informers for new developing and guides when we were coming to their community center for the recording.

153
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:47,000
We developed a huge new audience in an area that had been forgotten and I remember many times when these special stringers became the real source of new jet carrier students.

154
00:23:48,000 --> 00:24:05,000
We were the center of the talk and the party and this stringer would lead them around the community to where they wouldn't be hurt and they could come up with exclusive news which kept jet full.

155
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:18,000
We also had a column, a weekly column and jitter, take a tape where I could run two or three senses about little events that happened all across the country.

156
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:34,000
I used this to carry more information that these stringers would send up that never got a new figure until jet ran and it amazed me how the community sort of ignited.

157
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:43,000
It lit up over and it was very valuable.

158
00:24:43,000 --> 00:25:04,000
We had the stringer system too, I guess most of the publications did at that time because you didn't have a lot of bureaus in those places because we were so close to Mississippi, we were ending out of there and all for a lot.

159
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:17,000
When I talk about the culture down there, I think the till case was a good example of the kind of culture you ran into when you were covering those kind of stories.

160
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:23,000
I think a lot of the guys changed clothes quite often when they were down there.

161
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:34,000
The search for witnesses was the only time that I had changed clothes. I always went the way I worked when I was at the office around town.

162
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:48,000
But you ran into the situation where a lot of people were very helpful, some people were scared to talk, you know, their jobs were at stake and that sort of thing.

163
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:57,000
People were somewhat beaten down because of the system.

164
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:08,000
For example, of course it was not just little people on the street who would do things or say things who would actually kill people sometimes.

165
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:14,000
A lot of bodies were being found and people were actually afraid.

166
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:21,000
But the entire system worked that way.

167
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:30,000
The courthouse where they were having a till trial, of course it was segregated, you know, most of them were.

168
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:42,000
But how did the press operate? The sheriff told us when we got there, there had been no integration in my courthouse.

169
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:50,000
In addition to that, there was a press table there for white reporters and photographers and whatnot.

170
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:58,000
But not for black reporters. We were as often as the case to sit in the audience and that sort of thing.

171
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:06,000
Well, it happened that Congressman Charles Diggs from Detroit had come down as an observer.

172
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:14,000
And he and some of the veteran reporters complained to the judge about the situation.

173
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:20,000
So eventually they did set up a table off to the side where reporters could work.

174
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:28,000
And some of the other people were there, lawyers and whatnot, set at the same table over there.

175
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:35,000
So that was a sort of condition that you worked on everywhere.

176
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:38,000
You could hear what you could hear.

177
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:43,000
I remember covering a case, rape case, where some white women involved.

178
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:49,000
They had raped a co-ed on a tala haze, the University of Florida, A&M.

179
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:57,000
And most of the time I was sitting up in the balcony trying to hear as best you could.

180
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:03,000
But quite often that was just a situation.

181
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:11,000
Every single facet of life was pretty much segregated.

182
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:17,000
But you went out there to do a job.

183
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:32,000
And most of us thought that it was very important because newspapers had a way of writing what they wanted to write and leaving out what they wanted to leave out.

184
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:44,000
The first time I saw a story about Till being killed, I was probably two or three answers in the commercial appeal on a press semester, one of the two there in Memphis.

185
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:50,000
Once you get down there, it's a little different situation.

186
00:28:50,000 --> 00:29:01,000
I was just a Paul that I afraid people were to talk about the situation.

187
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:05,000
That's a good reason.

188
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:16,000
Let me ask you both about what memories especially come to your mind when you think about the work you did covering Little Rock in 57.

189
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:29,000
We were out at Little Rock very early with a team, a photographer, and we stayed on a case.

190
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:40,000
I got to know all the kids, the parents, even before the story broke like it did.

191
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:53,000
I think that's good to know stories like that and then write it so that people could get an idea of who these people were, what they were going through.

192
00:29:53,000 --> 00:30:08,000
Rather than say six kids showed up at the school, you got a chance to go to the inside and how the community grow to help them keep up them around.

193
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:22,000
Another thing that opened a white and a bureau, and I was very unusual those days, and we saw a big bureau that we covered Congress,

194
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:34,000
we covered the different government departments, the program, and state governments, and government legislation.

195
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:48,000
We did a lot of material that gave us enough material to fill our magazine and to cover with unusual ideas for everything.

196
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:59,000
Little Rock turned out to be one of the most important of all the civil rights cases.

197
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:05,000
It was sort of a long drawn out sort of a situation.

198
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:16,000
First off, arrangements had been made for the nine youngsters who were selected to integrate the school.

199
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:31,000
And on the verge of the day when they were supposed to enter school, government fathers changed his mind and said school was not going to be integrated.

200
00:31:32,000 --> 00:31:38,000
And to see that his orders were carried out, he called out the National Guard.

201
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:50,000
My first day over there, I was walking across Park, school was located there, Park in 16th.

202
00:31:51,000 --> 00:32:08,000
And I was met by Colonel who came out and greeted me and told me that I wouldn't be able to work up there because of my very presence might result in problems.

203
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:15,000
Now they had a bunch of white reporters over there and photographers and all that sort of thing.

204
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:26,000
But to make sure that I got his message, he had some of his troops to escort me out of the area, back to my car.

205
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:34,000
And as it happened, you always pick up a couple of guys who don't follow you with all kinds of threats and that sort of thing.

206
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:36,000
It was just two of them.

207
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:37,000
So I went to her about them.

208
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:41,000
And I had a camera and a strobe unit and that sort of thing.

209
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:57,000
But this situation in Lillrock, as Booker was explaining, we spent a lot of time hanging around the home of LC and Daisy Bates.

210
00:32:57,000 --> 00:33:08,000
Mrs. Bates was head of the NAACP and she was the one who was actually working closest with the nine students.

211
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:19,000
And we'd hang around that paper, hang around the home, the kid would come in and dance and doing what kids do, reading or refrigerator and that sort of thing.

212
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:23,000
So you did get to know them pretty well.

213
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:36,000
Next time we were up there when this kid was supposed to go to school, we bumped into this big crowd of people who were lined up on the streets out there.

214
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:46,000
And they were four of us, myself and the LLX Wilson, who had been my boss at the Tri-State Defender.

215
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:53,000
This was my first story for the Afro-American newspapers in Baltimore.

216
00:33:53,000 --> 00:34:04,000
And as we went up, the mob was sent in and where you guys are going and you're never going to get back from up there and this kind of stuff.

217
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:09,000
And we were putting up ID cards and that kind of stuff.

218
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:13,000
It didn't mean anything and they told you that doesn't mean anything.

219
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:18,000
You'd put that egg in, you know, they were calling all kinds of names and that sort of thing.

220
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:26,000
So eventually, someone from up front yelled that the kids were getting into the school.

221
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:33,000
They had come around another way and that's when all hell broke loose.

222
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:37,000
They started attacking us.

223
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:49,000
And I suppose you've seen some pictures of LLX Wilson getting kicked and beat up and guys climbing on his back and hitting him with brakes and that sort of thing.

224
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:58,000
I was sort of walking at that time with Jimi Hicks with the Amtadown News at the time.

225
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:05,000
We sort of ran along to stay out of the way of these guys.

226
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:09,000
We just took a few leaks, you know, that sort of thing.

227
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:19,000
But LLX Wilson, I had worked with him for five years at the Defender and I was trying to encourage him to come along with us.

228
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:37,000
But it turned out that LLX Wilson had had a problem with the KKK down in Leesburg, Florida, where I had gone to school after I reached the senior level.

229
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:48,000
I didn't know Mr. Wilson but we rode two and from work a lot of times down there and ran a little incident one evening when

230
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:55,000
we had stopped at it. I was house there and problem came up.

231
00:35:55,000 --> 00:36:08,000
And after that some guy was waving and going, I mean he just walked slowly along and I didn't know what was going on or what the situation was.

232
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:14,000
So I jumped out and sort of interceded and told the guy we were leaving and getting away.

233
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:23,000
But that was the first time that he told me that he had run into problems with the KKK down in Leesburg.

234
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:32,000
And he had run and he made a place to himself that never again would he run under that sort of a situation.

235
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:39,000
So that's why he wouldn't run at LLX and that's why he got beat up pretty badly.

236
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:53,000
And his wife, Imaging, she still thinks that Beaton he took there, sort of hasten his early demise.

237
00:36:53,000 --> 00:37:08,000
But the reason I say that that was one of the most important of all the civil rights cases that after they attacked us that day with the NAACP and others complaining about the fact that we weren't getting away.

238
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:13,000
And then he had no protection down there.

239
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:18,000
President Eisenhower decided to send in the military.

240
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:33,000
And what that meant was that no more would people be able to use violence to actually prevent desegregation activities from taking place.

241
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:40,000
As a matter of fact, I thought we would never see that sort of a situation again.

242
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:53,000
But later as I found out and going down to Mississippi, the case of James Meredith, people were still trying to do it the violent way.

243
00:37:53,000 --> 00:38:06,000
But that was an extremely important case and it meant that people would have protection both reporters, kids who were trying to get into these schools.

244
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:18,000
There were some of the bravest kids that all over the country. They were absolutely fantastic and people would say, why are you going out there?

245
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:24,000
These kids would go out there. You had to be there too.

246
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:33,000
One of the stories I always look back on is one morning when those kids weren't supposed to go to school.

247
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:38,000
One of them didn't get the word Elizabeth Eggford.

248
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:47,000
And she got up there by herself and the guard wouldn't let her through.

249
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:51,000
I think at first she thought there would be friends of hers.

250
00:38:51,000 --> 00:38:55,000
But she realized eventually that they weren't.

251
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:05,000
And she started to leave in a group of white people surrounding her and just gave her a hard time, absolutely.

252
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:11,000
And we weren't up there because they weren't supposed to be there that day.

253
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:18,000
And as soon as I heard about it, I went out to a house and was talking to her.

254
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:31,000
And she said something that a 15-year-old kid would say, I never thought people could be so cruel.

255
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:36,000
And I made it to the leader of a story. It got played in the paper.

256
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:40,000
Someone else also did a very good story on it.

257
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:45,000
But those were the kind of things you would run into out there.

258
00:39:45,000 --> 00:40:00,000
And from time to time, you just had to stop writing and just listen to people talking about what they went through as individuals out there trying to just get an education.

259
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:10,000
Okay, we're back on after that. They're short break.

260
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:24,000
I want to ask you both about, before we turn to the freedom ride, I want to ask you both about, as far as you can recall, what was your mood about the prospects for race relations, say by the, just, just the early 60s?

261
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:31,000
Canadi has been elected there in the fall of 60.

262
00:40:31,000 --> 00:40:40,000
But you'd seen things like Little Rock plus and minuses. I guess the pluses that Eisenhower exerted federal authority.

263
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:49,000
But minuses are pretty tough situations still. And do you recall what you moved about the prospects for race relations work?

264
00:40:49,000 --> 00:41:03,000
Well, Eisenhower, he just, he came to civil rights with a blank. I remember after he went out of office, I went over the interview and had a retirement.

265
00:41:03,000 --> 00:41:15,000
And he said to me, all the questions, you asked me all of them on civil rights. And I said, now my opportunity.

266
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:22,000
I said, well, that was the one subject you never talked about, what are your questions?

267
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:36,000
You always never came out. I could, Kennedy, crazy, started it. He got going. And then unfortunately, he got killed.

268
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:47,000
And so the different, I was named a Paul Barrett at his funeral, something on a early November day.

269
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:57,000
But he really opened it up to the press. I had a season of second row. He really, now I'm just talking.

270
00:41:57,000 --> 00:42:06,000
But he did play to show back your part of this too.

271
00:42:06,000 --> 00:42:14,000
Mr. Newton, you remember your, your moved around the time of Kennedy's election?

272
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:29,000
Yeah, I think everybody sort of expected somewhat more than what was actually done.

273
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:42,000
They, they set a good mood with some of the speeches they were making and, and that sort of thing, which was good for the country,

274
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:54,000
because there had to be another voice out there beside what some of the media were doing and what some of the seven lawmakers were doing.

275
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:07,000
And what they were saying, you know, about pulling out of the union and disobeying laws and that kind of stuff.

276
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:26,000
We had a lot of different organizations working tirelessly, you know, the NACP and Urban League and core, the young people in SNCC.

277
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:48,000
Some of the most encouraging thing was some of the courts, some of the judges who started making some very important rulings, knocking down Jim Probe, Barriers, Johnson, Warrant and some of the others,

278
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:59,000
who were very, very important in setting the stage for some of the progress that would take place later.

279
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:04,000
All these guys, all these things were encouraging.

280
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:17,000
I don't know if anybody saw the changes coming, the way they eventually came about as earlier because,

281
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:29,000
you know, people who talk about the 50s and the 60s, but people had been fighting the long, long time, this struggle had been going on for ages.

282
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:41,000
People were getting killed out there. We had a family in Old Florida get done about it doing it on holiday season, Christmas holiday season.

283
00:44:41,000 --> 00:45:01,000
So it was not just that one period, but I do believe that when they killed Emmett Till, supposedly for whistling a white woman,

284
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:14,000
I think people took sort of a different attitude. Now they killed our kids, and kids also took a different attitude.

285
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:27,000
I think a lot of the young people began to become more assertive, more active.

286
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:43,000
A lot of adults became more active in putting themselves on the line to help bring about some of the changes that would take place.

287
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:53,000
People really don't know about a lot of the activities that were taking place, a lot of the prices that people paid.

288
00:45:53,000 --> 00:46:08,000
I remember being in a little church greeting movement down in Mississippi, not too far from where money was located.

289
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:22,000
And we had people inside, including some of the top civil rights people, and the speaker there was professor at Howard University.

290
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:38,000
And outside you have the police, KKK and other student people's pictures. They were doing that so that they could kick people off the plantations and fire them and that kind of stuff.

291
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:52,000
And during the meeting, we had another one of those moments where people sang songs about not letting them turn around, turn them around.

292
00:46:52,000 --> 00:46:59,000
And after we sang somebody would get up and talk about an experience that they had.

293
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:11,000
And eventually this guy, I guess it was middle-aged guy, something he gets up and he was telling them about his situation.

294
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:17,000
And the situation was that he had been on this farm for ages, Shackropper.

295
00:47:17,000 --> 00:47:22,000
And he had gone over to try to register vote.

296
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:30,000
And now the owner was telling him that he had a few days to find someplace to go.

297
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:39,000
He's got this family, several kids, he's got no job, no transportation, no access to places to go.

298
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:52,000
And he tells these people, don't do anything for me, don't worry about me. Just get out there and try to register and vote.

299
00:47:52,000 --> 00:47:56,000
Man, it was one of those moments that you have out there.

300
00:47:56,000 --> 00:48:06,000
They raised money for the guy at James Farm, it was there and some other one they would say that more money would be coming.

301
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:13,000
But that was the kind of pressure these people were actually living under.

302
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:25,000
You know how to pull these and fire trucks running up and down outside the church with the bells clanging and ringing and shooting people's pitches so they could turn them over to the bosses.

303
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:32,000
And people were getting fired up and right. People with no money, no funds, no place to go.

304
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:37,000
So they were paying a real heavy price now.

305
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:44,000
And you didn't hear about those stories a lot of times, but they were going on.

306
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:58,000
And some of the bravest people out there were guys like Moses, sneak guys who would sell down in these little towns and stay for weeks.

307
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:03,000
You know, I grew out here on a story and things cooled off a little bit.

308
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:09,000
You know, I was gone back to Baltimore, but these people were there day in and day out.

309
00:49:09,000 --> 00:49:13,000
And I don't know how some of them did it.

310
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:26,000
I'm going to ask you both about an experience where you were very, very close to some very, very tough history, which was the Freedom Ride.

311
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:37,000
And I'm interested if you can think back about how each of you first was asked to consider participating in the bus ride as a journalist.

312
00:49:37,000 --> 00:49:42,000
Do you remember who first reached out to you or how the...

313
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:59,000
Well, on the Freedom Ride, I went to Baltimore and said, look, I want to go with you to see what happens with a photographer.

314
00:49:59,000 --> 00:50:09,000
And we went, not as a participant, but as a bluerbist.

315
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:20,000
But I don't know if there was any difference, because people didn't take time to say he's a bluerbist or a participant.

316
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:24,000
And that was an eye out.

317
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:26,000
And we went all the way.

318
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:44,000
We went from Washington after the Selma and Natty Era, when one bus was burned and the motor was on that bus.

319
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:46,000
I was on the other bus.

320
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:55,000
We got to Birmingham, I looked at the window and I would see this crowd, if you would change and all that kind of stuff.

321
00:50:55,000 --> 00:51:07,000
I ducked out the back of the bus and luckily hail the black cab driver who took me to take a gun.

322
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:08,000
You remember the shuttle was time?

323
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:10,000
The shuttle was time.

324
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:20,000
And the call candidate's office and said, man, you got to get out of here.

325
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:24,000
These people in trouble.

326
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:27,000
And they said, well, you saved life.

327
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:31,000
I'm going to go on that for a second there.

328
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:33,000
That was a real experience.

329
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:35,000
But my contribution was not whole.

330
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:38,000
I'm just finishing the book.

331
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:41,000
My experience is on the front line.

332
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:52,000
And another two or three months I hope to be able to take it to an agent and say, look, come and get this problem.

333
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:54,000
But again, I put in a lot of material.

334
00:51:54,000 --> 00:52:01,000
It's not an agent book on the rise of blacks.

335
00:52:01,000 --> 00:52:08,000
Because I was in many different events and at different angles.

336
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:11,000
But you could see a lot of problems.

337
00:52:11,000 --> 00:52:13,000
You didn't see from this area.

338
00:52:13,000 --> 00:52:15,000
But you saw over here.

339
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:24,000
And one follow up on, because you were in DC as bureau chief, you were able to forge some relationships with people inside the administration.

340
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:27,000
I had a lot of contact with him.

341
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:30,000
And I was in the FBI.

342
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:45,000
Or I got all close and listen with the presidents, you know, with the administration, the department.

343
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:48,000
And you could see what you could do.

344
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:54,000
Plus, I was a slick fellow those days, not anymore.

345
00:52:54,000 --> 00:52:59,000
I was a Westinghouse real commentary three times a week.

346
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:10,000
So what the black community, I could get over in the white community and do things to explain what black was doing here.

347
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:14,000
And then really open up a lot of it.

348
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:20,000
I could see where blacks had a little prayer, a daily prayer.

349
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:31,000
But you get over in, dropping commentary on something subject with a creative, much stirred, and within the black community.

350
00:53:31,000 --> 00:53:34,000
So I played a lot of kind of games and over there.

351
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:38,000
I'm too old to do that.

352
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:45,000
I always just like to work with Simmons Booker because,

353
00:53:45,000 --> 00:54:01,000
you know, you could depend on, you didn't have to worry about some guy trying to, you know, go on out there and say something or doing something that gets you in more trouble than you were already in just being out there.

354
00:54:01,000 --> 00:54:14,000
We got a call from Jim Palmer, even when it's someone to come out two weeks and go on the journey with them.

355
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:19,000
And I agreed to go.

356
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:34,000
At the time, I had already accepted invitations to come down to New Orleans to cover voting rights here and that would be inhaled by the Civil Rights Commission.

357
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:46,000
The day they left on May 4, 1961, I had gone down to do that story and came back and had a few things to do in office.

358
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:54,000
I didn't catch up with the freedom writers until they were at North Carolina, A&T College.

359
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:58,000
I just like to mention a little story that I did down in North Carolina.

360
00:54:58,000 --> 00:55:02,000
It's one of those stories that don't get much play.

361
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:21,000
We had a registrar there who was testifying over and over and over how she would give these little simple tests and all the white people could pass the test, but none of the white people could pass the test.

362
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:27,000
And that's why none of them were being registered there in that area of Louisiana.

363
00:55:27,000 --> 00:55:42,000
So the lawyers from the Civil Rights Commission, they got to understand and they started asking her some of these simple questions that she said that the black applicants couldn't answer.

364
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:45,000
And a few of the simple questions.

365
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:52,000
And she sat there and she couldn't answer any of those questions, not any of them.

366
00:55:52,000 --> 00:56:03,000
And we were trying to be headline all the way across the paper saying that Dixie Voto, Oficial, Flunk's Own Test.

367
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:10,000
And that's the sort of thing. That's the way things were being done in the South.

368
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:27,000
But as I caught up with the freedom writers, what they were doing, you know, mixed groups would go all twos and threes at the time and go into these stations to test to see whether they could use the facilities and that sort of thing.

369
00:56:27,000 --> 00:56:36,000
I guess I shouldn't go through a long story, but there had been three rulings that made it possible for them to do this.

370
00:56:36,000 --> 00:56:45,000
Courage tried it back in 47 and didn't get too far because they really didn't have the legal support.

371
00:56:45,000 --> 00:57:00,000
And before then, there was a woman out of Baltimore who was coming out of Virginia and she refused to give up her seat.

372
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:09,000
So she won a case in 1946 that dealt with the interior travel.

373
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:18,000
After that, there was the Rose Park situation about 10 years later. The Rose Park situation down in Montgomery.

374
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:34,000
And eventually four women represented, Turner Fred Gray. Neither of them was Mrs. Poggs who was arrested, led to this famous boycott over a year long.

375
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:46,000
And I have this most incredible thing. The world I've never seen anything like that in the United States where these people got together and refused to ride the buses for that sort of period.

376
00:57:46,000 --> 00:57:54,000
But these four women who were plaintiffs in this case, they won an intra travel case.

377
00:57:54,000 --> 00:58:05,000
Then after that, I was a young fellow named Bruce Boynton. He refused to give up his seat in one of the bus stations.

378
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:14,000
And that resulted in a case that covered facilities. So now you know, you had three things done.

379
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:28,000
So when I watched them for a while and the first rear blotter, so out there was now Congressman John Lewis.

380
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:39,000
They got down to the place, Rock Hill, South Carolina. And he went in. A couple of the people went in with him to white people went in with him.

381
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:48,000
And they got attacked and got thrown out of that place. And Lewis was pretty blood in when he came out.

382
00:58:48,000 --> 00:59:02,000
Shortly after that, when we went at Latter, my Luther King came over. People would have these meetings, you know, with great freedom writers and that sort of thing.

383
00:59:02,000 --> 00:59:25,000
Not everybody was happy about what was going on. But my Luther King had told our good friend, Simon Booker here, and some others that he had heard that the KKKK and others were planning to see the freedom writers never got out of Alabama alive.

384
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:43,000
And that was a pretty serious situation. So to make matters worse, the day we were going to be leaving for Anderson Alabama, and that bus was going to be leaving to go another route ahead of the Birmingham.

385
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:51,000
James Palmer learned that his father had died and his mother wanted him to come back right away.

386
00:59:51,000 --> 01:00:05,000
So we had that situation where we didn't have our main leader there, but they were going to push on anyway. I was on the Greyhound bus that day. And I don't know the road.

387
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:17,000
I know the Greyhound bus hailed us down and told us to put a nice car in my butt at Anderson Alabama station at the Anderson Alabama Greyhound station.

388
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:37,000
And when we got there, sure enough, it was pretty angry mob there. And they were calling freedom writers all kind of names and, you know, niggas and communists come on out and integrate Alabama and that sort of stuff.

389
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:45,000
They were beaten on the buses with the bus with chains and sticks and whatever else they had.

390
01:00:45,000 --> 01:00:52,000
The bus driver had to take out the business there. He would lock the door when he got out. So nobody could get on the bus.

391
01:00:52,000 --> 01:01:05,000
And I guess I had another one that was little experiences. There was a woman on the bus that knew nothing about the freedom writers. She was coming home from a funeral.

392
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:19,000
She was sitting across the aisle from me and she was saying things like, why are they doing this to us? And I don't want to die here like this. And she was down on a knees between the two seats there.

393
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:29,000
So I go and try to tell her what was going on and sort of thing. And I was still watching the windows. I was still trying to break out the windows there.

394
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:43,000
And she told me I could use a name in my story. I didn't even remember the homes, I believe. And eventually, the bus driver got back in and we took off.

395
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:52,000
And at the time we got to the edge of the city. We heard that the sound of tires going down.

396
01:01:52,000 --> 01:02:06,000
And you could look back and you could see a line of cars that were following us. And there was a little road that stayed in front of the bus to keep the bus from picking up speed. So we saw the trap there.

397
01:02:06,000 --> 01:02:26,000
That's when we find out that there were a couple of white state troopers on the bus. We didn't know about it. They were playing clothes. And they started again breaking out windows and banging on the bus and daring people to come out and that sort of thing.

398
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:45,000
One of these guys, one of the state offices, L. Cowlin, he pulled his pistol and stood in the doorway to keep anybody from getting on the bus. And that's all the save that's right.

399
01:02:45,000 --> 01:03:03,000
They finally made a breakthrough, one of the windows and it threw this fire bomb thing in the seat just behind me, which is an empty seat. And I got a few burns on the back of the ear and that's all the thing. But nothing serious.

400
01:03:03,000 --> 01:03:18,000
Suddenly it was pitch black on that bus and a couple of people got out of the windows and caught rides. Several of us sort of trapped on the bus there until we could get out.

401
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:30,000
And I said, well, I'm going to be the last guy off this bus and the way it gets trapped on here. So I just put a hack into it with my mouth and nose and that sort of thing and hung around as long as I could.

402
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:47,000
And it started getting hot on there. It was time to get off. So we got out and I tell you when you step off that bus and you looked around and you saw these people crawling around trying to get there.

403
01:03:47,000 --> 01:04:14,000
And I was trying to get the smoke out of the chairs and people crawling, caw and gag and it was one of those sites that make you wonder why Americans are doing that sort of thing to fellow Americans who was just trying to exercise their rights.

404
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:23,000
And eventually that bus burned right down, brought open daylight and burned out this expensive Greyhound bus.

405
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:36,000
By the time I got off and saw these people shooting pictures I realized that I had stuck my camera upon the seat. It's pretty dangerous to be getting off in that situation with a camera on your neck.

406
01:04:36,000 --> 01:04:47,000
It burned up with the bus but I was able to contact the Greyhound company and get the bus back and get the camera back.

407
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:55,000
It's been all of you now that the New Zealand and Washington where people can see it they want to.

408
01:04:55,000 --> 01:05:09,000
But I was a pretty shaky occasion. The ones of us who were on that bus most of us the ones who didn't get out and catch rise were taken to the hospital there in the city.

409
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:20,000
And we just saw the stuff there. The young guy who's in charge of the bus in the absence of former Joe Perkins.

410
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:34,000
He was calling all around trying to get some battery helpers get out of their hospital. They were telling you can't stay here and the police were saying we can only protect you to just sit in line.

411
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:42,000
It was kind of dark out there. You know, we can hear those people out there still hanging around.

412
01:05:42,000 --> 01:05:54,000
Eventually he reached Revan Schoelsworth, Oven Birmingham. He agreed to send over Caravanne cars to get us out of there.

413
01:05:54,000 --> 01:06:07,000
And while we were waiting around, at the time after America was doing about 13 editions, the National Edition went to press on Sunday nights.

414
01:06:07,000 --> 01:06:17,000
I was able to step outside and get a telephone and call the night editor to tell him what kind of story I would have the next day.

415
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:27,000
And as him to call my wife and tell her that I was okay. But he's got a tough duty sometimes after.

416
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:31,000
Let's take a break.

417
01:06:31,000 --> 01:06:44,000
I want to pick up on the day March, May the 14th, 1961.

418
01:06:44,000 --> 01:06:57,000
I'm just so struck by how so close each of you came to the prospect of just very serious injury or death in Aniston.

419
01:06:57,000 --> 01:07:06,000
And then when you stepped off that bus in Birmingham at the terminal, the course people were getting beaten so badly.

420
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:13,000
And somehow folks just missed catching a look at you before you began that gap.

421
01:07:13,000 --> 01:07:23,000
I wanted to get much of a chance to get this empty show up. I wanted to show it all about going.

422
01:07:23,000 --> 01:07:30,000
But it was a very close moment. I wear it so many close moments.

423
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:38,000
Because that was part of the life. And you just accepted it.

424
01:07:38,000 --> 01:07:47,000
I wonder, I'm thinking about the stretch of time between the Freedom Ride and the March on Washington those couple of years.

425
01:07:47,000 --> 01:07:53,000
And I remember the speech that John Lewis gave at the March on Washington.

426
01:07:53,000 --> 01:07:58,000
It was full of so much frustration with the government for its reluctance.

427
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:05,000
The Kennedy administration for its reluctance to step in and aid people in the South who were suffering white violence.

428
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:21,000
And I'm wondering kind of how each of you felt coming out of an experience like the Freedom Ride and what perspectives you came away with on that question or others.

429
01:08:21,000 --> 01:08:24,000
Just what it looked like you feeling you're thinking.

430
01:08:25,000 --> 01:08:38,000
Well, my anger was the big deeper and coverage of this underclass of blacks.

431
01:08:38,000 --> 01:08:43,000
Opened up some more of them given opportunities.

432
01:08:43,000 --> 01:08:47,000
That's the only way you want to do anything.

433
01:08:48,000 --> 01:09:05,000
People can't get education training. You don't get jobs or this and so with Jeff and Ebony tried to educate and reach them.

434
01:09:05,000 --> 01:09:17,000
By them to send their kids to school, take an interest in education, clean them their health, all those things.

435
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:22,000
But that's a sort of an inward process.

436
01:09:22,000 --> 01:09:33,000
But it's one that you have to use as a brother to brother to sister for the work.

437
01:09:33,000 --> 01:09:39,000
You know, getting out of press or play is not front page new.

438
01:09:39,000 --> 01:09:46,000
And that's one of the real problems that you have.

439
01:09:46,000 --> 01:10:09,000
I think there was another one of the situations where the ambitions and aspirations of black people didn't exactly coincide with the administration's viewpoints.

440
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:23,000
How they saw their own jobs and what this kind of thing, how it could affect them in a different way.

441
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:29,000
There were just so many things that the general public didn't know about.

442
01:10:29,000 --> 01:10:47,000
That reporters were able to learn some of the background about things that Jay Ega Hoover was doing at the Justice Department.

443
01:10:47,000 --> 01:11:00,000
We saw these guys out there, FBI guys watching, but then they would come to you later and ask you what happened.

444
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:04,000
I'm going to take a lot of new rock. I want to try to get away.

445
01:11:04,000 --> 01:11:13,000
Some guy come later than I had to ask me what took place. And I saw him standing on the sidewalk.

446
01:11:13,000 --> 01:11:33,000
But he, again, not just to keep saying that one person, John Lewis and some of his younger folks weren't too happy with the way that the administration, the candidate administration,

447
01:11:33,000 --> 01:11:44,000
was trying to slow down some of the efforts at bringing about changes.

448
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:50,000
That became quite an issue there.

449
01:11:50,000 --> 01:12:03,000
But Demart was one of the historic things. I was sort of happy. It didn't happen often, but it was closed by Baltimore.

450
01:12:03,000 --> 01:12:19,000
I took my wife and a neighbor who was a wife of one of our photographers went along and were able to get that seat and take part in that event.

451
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:35,000
It was a great event. Sometimes you look back on it. You got to hear my Duke Kang a lot of this thing that turned out to be so great.

452
01:12:35,000 --> 01:12:46,000
I don't know over and over a number of times. But when he got a role in that day, the circumstances was so much different.

453
01:12:46,000 --> 01:13:05,000
But all these white union people and church leaders and everybody else bringing themselves together to demand that changes be made, it took on a completely different light.

454
01:13:05,000 --> 01:13:21,000
The impact of it was just great. He's another guy that people don't understand what he was going through a lot of times.

455
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:33,000
I know, shortly before his death, they were planning the pool of people's mods on Washington.

456
01:13:33,000 --> 01:13:55,000
I went down to Atlanta to interview him. As usual, he was running late and he and Andy Young had to catch a flight after they finally came out of this big meeting with all these people, pool of people in the young Latinos and whatnot.

457
01:13:55,000 --> 01:14:09,000
I had to interview him actually in a car going to the airport. It was kind of different. You got Andy Young there. You got his wife there. You got Harry Bellafonte there.

458
01:14:09,000 --> 01:14:33,000
You're trying to interview him about some of the problems that was going on. You know, there's FBI was taping him and leaking stuff. Some of the civil rights leaders were saying that his position on the wall was causing him to lose sight of what he was doing.

459
01:14:33,000 --> 01:14:52,000
That sort of thing. They were having trouble raising money at the time. He eventually had to ask him what's your reaction to all this and that people were saying that you were failing at what you were supposed to be doing.

460
01:14:52,000 --> 01:15:12,000
He said something that really struck me. He said that when I was surprised to hear, he said, if I'm failing, then you might say according to the way some people look at it, Jesus Christ failed because He got himself hung on the cross.

461
01:15:12,000 --> 01:15:36,000
I think that story ran about the middle of March in the year that he died. It was just a few weeks before he died. It was a strange thing. He was on the lot of stress that a lot of people didn't know and didn't appreciate.

462
01:15:36,000 --> 01:15:56,000
He was struggling with all the charges about the communist associations and all the rumors, the type of stuff that a lot of people had printed before that they started printing and trying to bring him down.

463
01:15:56,000 --> 01:16:20,000
He was quite an interesting guy. He was a brave guy. Not an awful lot of people would have gone through what he went through and kept the front that he kept up there and plugging away as he plugged away day after day.

464
01:16:20,000 --> 01:16:34,000
Mr. Booker, do you have special recollections of Barnard the King and Gawson, to all the work you did covering the movement in River King?

465
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:58,000
Well, he was very unusual there. I've never seen him just appointed or defeated. He always seemed to be on the make, on the go. I couldn't ever figure out, he never gave up.

466
01:16:58,000 --> 01:17:20,000
He was in a very difficult situation. He always stayed out with a little prayer to himself and he kept on. A lot of people said, oh, he always gone on. He never did. He stayed with...

467
01:17:20,000 --> 01:17:36,000
How did you cover up Malcolm X? No, I didn't. There was an area Malcolm X, Stoke, a whole cry. I never paid much attention to it.

468
01:17:36,000 --> 01:17:50,000
I was like the whole deal was to grab the press attention. They went in, they knew I had grabbed certain sections of it.

469
01:17:50,000 --> 01:18:10,000
The rest was Royal Wilkins, Whitney. I remember Whitney when he was died in somewhere in Europe. I had to fly over to one plane, pick up his body.

470
01:18:10,000 --> 01:18:30,000
I was in Nigeria. I think we went on that flat together. We went down on Air Force One. President Nixon flew down to participate in the services down there for Whitney Young.

471
01:18:30,000 --> 01:18:38,000
Simon and I were among the people who went down to cover that event.

472
01:18:38,000 --> 01:18:52,000
Let me take you back for just a minute. Is there more that you'd like to add about... obviously we could talk for hours on this thing, but are there other things that come to your mind when you think about what we came covering human beings?

473
01:18:52,000 --> 01:19:08,000
No, actually I didn't get to cover him too much. We had a staff in Baltimore and usually when he came to Baltimore he was covered by some of the other staff people there.

474
01:19:08,000 --> 01:19:26,000
I sat in on a lot of the speeches he would make, but I didn't actually cover him. It was fascinating to see him and Abanath they were working together. Abanath would pass the basket and collect the money.

475
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:46,000
King would make those great speeches that he was known for. But they were quite a tool when they were working together. I was done in Alabama in the Black Belt, there for a while after King died.

476
01:19:46,000 --> 01:20:03,000
Abanath was trying to carry on his work and it just wasn't working the way everyone had hoped it would. But he gave it his best shot at it.

477
01:20:03,000 --> 01:20:11,000
He didn't have the personality that Dr. King had.

478
01:20:11,000 --> 01:20:24,000
Was either of you and other of you covered the Democratic National Convention in Atlantic City in August of 64 with the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party controversy?

479
01:20:24,000 --> 01:20:53,000
I covered four conventions to Republicans, to Democrats, a couple of Miami Beach and New York and that significant one in the Republican one in Kansas and Missouri there when the conservative wing took over the party.

480
01:20:53,000 --> 01:20:59,000
But I didn't do 64.

481
01:20:59,000 --> 01:21:20,000
One more question, then we can take a little break and come back and finish up. I'm interested in your thoughts about evolving relations between Black journalists and white journalists and earliest efforts at beginning now to staff some black journalists on to larger white papers and just pass this period.

482
01:21:20,000 --> 01:21:27,000
I'm interested in your thoughts on the relations between Black press and the White Press.

483
01:21:27,000 --> 01:21:41,000
I thought there was a reason they had different standards. The white press would pick off the prominent black whatever.

484
01:21:41,000 --> 01:22:00,000
The black press, they were kind of local politics and all, but it was a very difficult kind of thing to stand as to where they stand as a fidget holder.

485
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:16,000
I covered all the conventions, but so long ago I wouldn't remember one of them. My memory is good.

486
01:22:16,000 --> 01:22:31,000
I don't know. I didn't have the usual contact that a lot of the other reporters we had would have.

487
01:22:31,000 --> 01:22:44,000
I was, if I went to Baltimore, I was only on the beat for about a year and then I got moved into the office and won eight inches job, one in a position of another.

488
01:22:44,000 --> 01:23:13,000
Before that, when I was in Memphis, I knew quite a few of the guys. In covering stories, it was somewhat different because normally they would stay at some hotel or something of some motel that would be central headquarters for a lot of them.

489
01:23:13,000 --> 01:23:27,000
We were not able to stay at those places. Some of the guys we got along when we were working, I could answer some things for them sometimes.

490
01:23:27,000 --> 01:23:36,000
They could help me with things, sometimes on meetings that I wasn't able to get to.

491
01:23:36,000 --> 01:23:50,000
By and large, it was a professional relationship I would call it. I didn't do a lot of hanging out with anybody.

492
01:23:50,000 --> 01:24:05,000
In particular, for five years, I spent a lot of time down in Mississippi. They had papers with Karen things which were pretty much opposite to what I was writing and what I was emphasizing.

493
01:24:05,000 --> 01:24:24,000
They were emphasizing something else. Frankly, you didn't know who was who. There was no need to be glad about a lot with people. You didn't know what they were writing, what was going on.

494
01:24:24,000 --> 01:24:33,000
I didn't really go out of my way to try to have a great social relationship with them.

495
01:24:33,000 --> 01:24:53,000
We're back. We're back up there, a little break. We're just going to finish up. Mr. Booker, I want to ask for your thoughts about being print reporters in an era when television came on to really do so much.

496
01:24:53,000 --> 01:25:08,000
I want to do so much to impact the way that the American public at large reacted to the Civil Rights story. Let me just open up with that. Any thoughts or reflections you might have on that question?

497
01:25:08,000 --> 01:25:23,000
I think when the White Press really became involved in covering the Civil Rights story as a movement, nothing greater could have happened.

498
01:25:23,000 --> 01:25:43,000
They had the TV networks and that was just invaluable. They would show how people were being treated. They did some great interviews.

499
01:25:43,000 --> 01:26:04,000
I always had to feel that Americans as a whole, although they were not really anxious to bring up and see the changes that were taking place.

500
01:26:04,000 --> 01:26:19,000
Deep down, there was sort of a feeling in America that justice was important and treating people a certain way was important.

501
01:26:19,000 --> 01:26:40,000
When those screens were showing people being beaten, forced down by hoses and trampled over by horses, I think it had a great impact.

502
01:26:40,000 --> 01:27:03,000
It was something that the Black Press could not do at the time. Some of the coverage shows a great effort to get people thinking a different way.

503
01:27:03,000 --> 01:27:23,000
I think it was very successful. I don't think the movement would have been able to do the things at the speed that it was done without those images.

504
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:39,000
They were just greatly important to move things to where it is now. The media as a whole have been quite helpful.

505
01:27:39,000 --> 01:28:01,000
I still have some questions sometimes about some of the coverage. I will get into that. It was just a long story. I tell you one example. It was the story involved to profess it up at Harvard and the way it was treated.

506
01:28:01,000 --> 01:28:21,000
This was a disorderly conduct thing that would not have stood up in the court in this country because the court said that American citizens can call a policeman a name. You can yell at a policeman. You can demand to see his ID.

507
01:28:21,000 --> 01:28:45,000
That is all that the sergeant charge him with. Press told us, media told us in great details that the Black Office had seen was 100% behind the sergeant. His command said he was just doing what he was trained to do.

508
01:28:45,000 --> 01:29:03,000
Nobody was emphasizing in mainstream media that this was such a bad arrest that it wouldn't hold up in any court. I mean for decades these rulings had been made quite obviously.

509
01:29:03,000 --> 01:29:25,000
The mainstream press didn't do the job on it. There were a lot of blogs that were doing cable stations. I was talking about New York Times and Washington Post. They wanted to tell them people that this was a case that would not stand up in any court.

510
01:29:25,000 --> 01:29:35,000
Most of them didn't even tell you why the case was dropped. Pigeon said it was dropped and the charges were dropped.

511
01:29:35,000 --> 01:29:45,000
The media has done a great job but from time to time you see covers that some of it's suspect.

512
01:29:45,000 --> 01:29:52,000
That was the professor gates in 2009. I believe it.

513
01:29:52,000 --> 01:30:12,000
Mr. Booker, a final question. I know in 68 following the assassination of Robert Kennedy that you had had connections to the Kennedy's and to Robert Kennedy and I think participated in his funeral.

514
01:30:12,000 --> 01:30:24,000
In 1968 after Bobby Kennedy's death. Did you have recollections of that experience?

515
01:30:24,000 --> 01:30:44,000
Well, I think it was a very sad occasion. I think he was the first official of that right to be sensitive to racial matters and actually did something about it.

516
01:30:44,000 --> 01:30:54,000
Others would talk about it, not publicly to us, but he was very frank and did a lot of things.

517
01:30:54,000 --> 01:31:06,000
But then he got killed and it sort of wiped out. Linda came along completely different in the visual.

518
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:23,000
He just won. He couldn't accept criticism until he couldn't deal with a whole lot of blacks with different views.

519
01:31:23,000 --> 01:31:49,000
He had to be the boss of anything. So everything ended there. And op-op political structure seemed to disintegrate and we're now trying to rebuild again, which we finally did when Obama came through.

520
01:31:49,000 --> 01:32:04,000
But then it still splitted on the white side. It's not a unity. So I guess America will always be.

521
01:32:04,000 --> 01:32:12,000
I hope that we'll all have a chance to extend our conversation at some point because it's been just wonderful to be with you both. Thank you so much.

522
01:32:12,000 --> 01:32:27,000
Thank you. This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

